        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
                    <marginalia_text>Nulla Culpa, aut mora, in Meipso esse debet, ullo uel minimo Tempore: Etiam Externi
                    defectus, omni modo curiosissim&egrave; supplendi. Mearu[m] maximaru[m] maxima; ascripta Galateo.
                    { Aut Tacendu[m], aut loquendu[m] meliora: Aut non mouendu[m], aut promouendum. Utrinq[ue] Vincenti gloria Victi.</marginalia_text>
                    <book title="Galateo: The Rules of Polite Behavior"/>
                    <X-ref person="Edmund Spenser" book_title="The Shepheardes Calender"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>There ought to be not faults or obstacles in myself in any or in the least time: nevertheless external defects are most
            curiously supplied in any way. The greatest of my greatests; inserted in Galateo.
            Either passing over or mentioning better things: Either not strirring or moving forward [better things]. Either way, "the glory of the defeated goes to the conqueror."</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Fortune bearith A great swey in fower things: In Marraiges: in [the] fauours of princes: in Warres: &amp; in
                    nauigation.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Fower main chances.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Fortuna fortes metuit: ignauos premit:
                    Seneca in Medea. Intrepida constent uerba: qui ti[m]id&egrave; rogat, docet negare: Ide[m] in Hippolito.
                    Prudentia sibi serua reddit omnia. Menander.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Seneca"/>
                    <person name="Menander"/>
                    <book title="Medea"/> <!--JG: Part of his tragedies, so tag as such instead of as Medea?-->
                    <book title="Phaedra"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>"Fortune fears the brave, overhelms the cowards". Seneca in 'Medea'. "Fearless be thy words, and firm; who makes timid request, invites denial." [Frank Justus Miller, 'The tragedies of Seneca']
            The same author in Hippolito. 
            Prudence renders all slaves to themselves. Menander.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
